## OVERVIEW:
This project is an implementation of a Nondeterministic Finite automata in Java,
where NFAs can be instantiated as a class and given a defined 5-tuple of language,
states, start state, final states, and transitions. The NFA can read strings and
determine if they would be accepted, or the max copies the machine will produce at
once while operating on a string.

## INCLUDED FILES
    * NFA.java - source file
    * NFAState.java - source file
    * README - this file

## COMPILING AND RUNNING:
From the directory containing all source files, compile the
driver class (and all dependencies) with the command:
* $ javac -cp .:/usr/share/java/junit.jar ./test/nfa/NFATest.java

Run the compiled class file with the command:
* $ java -cp .:/usr/share/java/junit.jar:/usr/share/java/hamcrest/hamcrest.jar org.junit.runner.JUnitCore test.nfa.NFATest

Console output will give the results after the program finishes.
## PROGRAM DESIGN AND IMPORTANT CONCEPTS:
The NFA class is responsible for managing the different parts of 
the NFAState objects. Each NFAState object contains a HashMap of 
transitions, which consists of mapping a character to a NFAState. 
Each NFAState also has the method getTransitions(), which returns 
a HashSet of NFAStates in order to represent a state having multiple 
transition states mapped to the same character symbol.

The NFA class outlines all the methods in both the FA and NFA Interface 
classes. Most importantly, the NFA class contains the method logic 
for the eClosure() and accepts() methods. The eClosure() method 
uses a stack to check through each state that can be accessed with 
an empty character (represented by e). It loops through the current 
state being accessed and, if it finds an e transition, it adds that 
state to the list of returned states and pushes that state on top 
of the stack. When the stack is empty, all possible states that can 
be accessed on an e have been iterated through.

The accepts() method uses a private method to conduct a BFS using 
the given string to recreate a trace of the string through the NFA. 
For each character in the string, the method searches through all 
possible transitions on that character. If the character can be 
consumed, it is removed and the machine continues until the string 
is empty and all characters have been consumed. If the machine has
halted, all characters have been consumed, and at least one copy of
the machine is in an accept state, the machine will return a positive
number, indicating the string has been accepted and is a member of
the NFA's language.


## TESTING:
The current code passes all of the given tests. In addition to those tests, 
three more test classes were written (test4_1-6, test5_1-6, and test6_1) to test functionality. 
In test4, bad input was tested by attempting to add transitions on non-existent 
states and on characters that were not members of the alphabet. This test also 
included e transitions so that a final state could be reached without any other 
input and multiple strings were used to check if it correctly accepted and denied 
strings based on this. The next test, test5, created a DFA and specifically tested 
the isDFA() method to ensure it returned true when a NFA had no e transitions or 
more than one transition per character. Lastly, test6 was used to test the NFA 
toString() method.

## DISCUSSION:
I was initially worried about using a stack for the eClosure() method, but after 
looking up the javadocs for it and reminding myself how to use it in practice, it 
became quite simple. I was able to reference a lot of the code from the first project, 
which helped a lot with the formatting. The isDFA() method was also much more simple 
than I had initially anticipated, since we only needed to check 3 criteria. In this 
implementation, however, I realized it was even less, since we can't quite check that 
all members of the alphabet are being used because we included the empty character e 
as a member. Writing the new test cases also helped, since I was able to identify some 
issues in logic with some of the methods. I did also attempt to do the accepts() method 
using similar logic to the DFAState's accepts() method, but that didn't work out as 
well as I hoped. I did learn a new implementation for a BFS, even if it didn't end up 
being used in the code. -- Haylee

I was able to figure out how to set up the NFA and NFAState class by reviewing work
from P1. I wasn't fully sure how to tackle the NFA-specific functions at first, but
once eclosure() was written it clicked and I was able to set up my DFS method. I based
it on the formal trace of an NFA, where you complete the trace where rows represent
characters read and columns represent different machines. Debugging the tests step by
step enabled me to check edge cases and catch a few issues with the BFS. I feel like I
have a lot better of an understanding of the finished code this time compared to P1,
now that we've gone a bit further with the concept. --Dean

